Annotation.note:
A problem posed at International Mathematical Olympiad:
In a given right triangle $ABC$, the hypotenuse $BC$, length $a$, is divided into $n$ equal parts with $n$ an odd integer. The central part subtends an angle $\alpha$ at $A$. $h$ is the perpendicular distance from $A$ to $BC$. Prove that: $$\tan \alpha_n = \frac{4\,n\,h}{a\,n^2 - a}$$
\begin{keywords} geometry theorem proving \end{keywords}
